Marco Rubio has established a pretty decent lead in the polls, albeit not yet a blowout. Val Demings is a solid candidate and has done well in fundraising, but ultimately Florida has become more of a red state, and Rubio will benefit from the tailwinds of Republican voters turning out to vote for Governor DeSantis.

Likely the incumbent Republican will win over someone with little experience, even within the state. On top of that, it's an off-year election where Republics (specifically in the House) are expected to do well. Democrats have been coming up in the polls, but it is still a long shot.

I predict incumbent Senator Marco Rubio will defend his seat against Democrat Val Jennings. The state of Florida had a Budget surplus, increased education quality, and a strong Red voter base for up to 20 years. According to The Economist, current forecasts predict the seat will be Likely R as of September 7th. Furthermore, DDHQ and 538 also predicted Likely R in July and August. Finally, Rubio is endorsed by Donald Trump, with 92% of candidates endorsed by trump winning their seats.

I think Marco Rubio will probably edge out a victory in this race, but I think it will be closer than some predict - e.g., FiveThiryEight, which currently reports that Rubio wins 86 out of 100 election models. Rubio will likely benefit from the Red Wave, incumbent name recognition, and energized voters activated by inflation, the economy, and the culture wars (e.g., critical race theory, sending immigrants to Blue States, rising crime rates, alleged "voter fraud," etc.). But Val Demmings could also make a very strong showing among her voters for similar reasons. Concerns about an increasingly radical SCOTUS loom large, and fears over reproductive rights, guns, and climate change (especially in Florida, and in particular rising costs for things like home insurance in the state) give Demmings at least a fighting chance. Ultimately, it comes down to independent/undecided Floridians and turnout at the polls.

Marco Rubio is what I would consider a veteran senator because he was first elected in 2010. Also, he is well known because of a presidential campaign that at certain stages had a good bit of support. People are more likely to vote for someones name that they recognize when in the ballot box, so that favors Rubio. Also, it is Florida, which has leaned Republican for many years now. An independent has no chance of winning the Florida senate election.
